<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="58" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1341,1554]" box="[196,1436,1415,1442]" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,317,1415,1441]" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">Remarks.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Liu &amp; Yang, 2009" authorityName="Liu &amp; Yang" authorityYear="2009" box="[683,1081,1416,1442]" class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" genus="Brithura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jinpingensis">
<emphasis box="[683,858,1416,1441]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">B. jinpingensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Liu" box="[866,1081,1416,1442]" pageId="6" pageNumber="60" refString="Liu, Q.; Yang, D. (2009) Two new species of the genus Brithura Edwards from China, with a key to world species (Diptera, Tipulidae). Zootaxa 1991, 51 - 56." type="journal article" year="2009">
Liu &amp; Yang, 
<quantity box="[1022,1081,1416,1442]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.10286" pageId="6" pageNumber="58" unit="in" value="2009.0">2009</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in having orange abdomen. It
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1341,1554]" box="[151,1436,1453,1479]" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">
can be easily separated from 
<taxonomicName box="[489,662,1453,1478]" class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" genus="Brithura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jinpingensis">
<emphasis box="[489,662,1453,1478]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">B. jinpingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the color of the prescutum and structure of the hypopygium. In
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1341,1554]" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName box="[151,324,1491,1516]" class="Insecta" family="Tipulidae" genus="Brithura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jinpingensis">
<emphasis box="[151,324,1491,1516]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">B. jinpingensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the prescutum is reddish brown, and the outer gonostylus has no lateral spine. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[196,337,1527,1553]" pageId="6" pageNumber="58">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species name is based on the yellow antenna.
</paragraph>
